{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501208"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:25:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.54,0.06,0.02,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50256"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1734"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35520"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1490"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"50048"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50256"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old Indigenous woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of increasing right iliac fossa pain. She has anorexia and has vomited once. Her last menstrual period was four weeks ago and she has had regular intercourse since then with several partners. She uses condoms occasionally and is not taking any hormonal contraception. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears flushed and unwell. Her temperature is 37.8\u00b0C, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, pulse rate 105/min, respiratory rate 18/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. She has tenderness in the right iliac fossa with localised peritonism. Speculum examination shows a copious purulent discharge. Serum beta-hCG is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next diagnostic step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pelvic ultrasound","Endocervical swab","Urine microscopy, culture and sensitivity","White cell count","Transvaginal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms of pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), which is an infection of the upper female genital tract, including the uterus, fallopian tubes, and ovaries. It is most commonly caused by sexually transmitted infections (STIs), such as \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E, that ascend from the lower genital tract. It can also be caused by \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma genitalium \u003C/em\u003Eand \u003Cem\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E. There are a number of possible other causes for the symptoms in this woman including urinary tract infection, appendicitis and ovarian cyst accident. However, she has significant risk factors for PID: multiple sexual partners and irregular condom use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn endocervical swab\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important next step, as this will likely confirm the diagnosis of PID as well as identity the causative organism. Whilst examining this patient, it is likely that lower abdominal tenderness, cervical motion tenderness and adnexal tenderness were also reported. Following collection of swabs, it is then important to obtain a full blood count and inflammatory markers, and to offer screening for other sexually transmitted infections including HIV, hepatitis C and syphilis. Treatment should not be delayed whilst awaiting results, this patient has severe PID and antibiotic treatment as an inpatient is required. If there is an intrauterine contraceptive device insitu, this can remain but if there is no clinical improvement over 48-72 hours it should be removed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy, culture and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E (MCS) is not the correct answer as this patient has no urinary symptoms and a UTI would not adequately explain her presentation. Whilst many STIs can be identified on a first-pass urine collection, NAAT is the chosen testing method. Furthermore, in this case an endocervical swab is more appropriate as there is purulent cervical discharge which will be collected for testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA white cell count\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to be elevated in PID. However, it is a non-specific finding and will not confirm the diagnosis or change initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA pelvic or transvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may show thickened, fluid-filled fallopian tubes in PID known as hydrosalpinx. However, it is not the most appropriate next step as the diagnosis can usually be made on clinical grounds and confirmed with endocervical swabs. Transvaginal ultrasound is more invasive than a pelvic ultrasound, however will better show the pelvic reproductive organs. Whilst appendicitis is an important differential diagnosis, the patient\u0027s risk profile and examination finding of purulent cervical discharge suggest PID.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is an infection of the upper female genital tract, including the uterus, fallopian tubes, and ovaries, most commonly caused by sexually transmitted infections.","A high vaginal swab is an essential initial investigation in cases of suspected PID.","PID requires prompt antibiotic treatment to reduce the risk of long-term sequelae such as infertility, chronic pelvic pain and ectopic pregnancy."],"references":["Australian STI Guidelines: PID-Pelvic Inflammatory Disease. Accessed 2020 Apr 18. Available at:\u00a0http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au","The Red Book. 6.2 Sexually transmissible infections. In: RACGP [online]. Accessed 2020 Apr 18. Available at:\u00a0https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/red-book/communicable-diseases/sexually-transmissible-infections.","Antibiotic.\u00a0In: Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35520"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35520"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-09T14:00:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-10T11:09:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1734"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50256"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id"